{"text": "1.\n\nThis leads to\n\nid\n\ndt(\u03b11\u03b72) = 4irxy(\u03b72\n\n2\u2212\u03b12\n\n1)\u22122\u221a\n\n2\u2206\u03b12\n\n1\u03b72. (42)\n\nMajorana fermions satisfy that \u03b72\n\n2=\u03b12\n\n1=1\n\n2. Therefore,\n\nfrom the differentials, this equation becomes\n\nid\n\ndt(\u03b11\u03b72) =\u2212\u2206\u221a\n\n2\u03b72. (43)\n\n(i) Eq. (43) agrees with the Heisenberg equation of\n\nmotion \u02d9 \u03c4z= 2\u2206\u03c4y. In general, this equation leads to a\n\nunitary evolution in time. Suppose that \u03b11(t) and \u03b72(t)\n\nwould acquire a decoherence such that \u03b11(t)\u2192\u03b11.e\u2212t/\u03c41\n\nand\u03b72(t)\u2192\u03b72.e\u2212t/\u03c42, then on the left-hand side we\n\nwould have a function in e\u2212t\n\n\u03c41\u2212t\n\n\u03c42whereas on the right-\n\nhand side we have a function in e\u2212t/\u03c42. It is also interest-\n\ning to comment that the \u03c3zvariable related to the usual\n\nspin-boson model satisfies a similar equation as for the\n\n\u03c4zspin\n\n\u02d9\u03c3z= 2\u2206\u03c3y. (44)\n\nThe correspondence between the spin-boson models with\n\nthe\u03c3spin (of one sphere) and with the \u03c4spin can be\n\nunderstood as \u03c3z\u2192\u03c4x(corresponding to the variable\n\ncoupling to the bath), \u03c3y\u2192\u03c4yand\u03c3x\u2192 \u2212\u03c4z. In terms\n\nof the Majorana fermions \u03b11and\u03b72, Eq. (44) would im-\n\nply \u02d9\u03b11=\u22122\u2206\u03b72such that we verify that a solution with\n\nan exponential decoherence would now be possible. We\n\nalso verify the occurrence of decoherence when evaluat-\n\ning \u00a8\u03c3zto second-order in \u03bbk. Therefore, all these results\n\nagree with the fact that the Majorana fermions \u03b11and\u03b72\n\ncan admit a coherent unitary dynamics when the bath is\n\nlinearly coupled to the \u03c4-spin along xdirection. Below,\n\nwe verify the coherent dynamics in the x\u2212yplane for\n\nthe\u03c4-spin. For completness, we can also address the fact\n\nthat\u2206is yet an operator. Plugging Eq. (43) into Eqs.\n\n(40), we obtain\n\n\u00a8\u03b72=\u22124rxy\u02d9\u03b11\u22124\u22062\u03b72=\u0000\n\n\u221216r2\n\nxy\u22124\u22062\u0001\n\n\u03b72.(45)\n\n8\n\nIf the bath is prepared within the vacuum state, in the\n\nweak-coupling limit, when the noise is infinitesimal then\n\n\u22062is approximately equal to B2\n\nx. More precisely, from\n\nthe equations of motion we also have\n\n\u00a8bk+\u00a8b\u2020\n\nk= (i\u03c9k)2(bk+b\u2020\n\nk) + 2\u03bbk\u03c9k\u03c4x.", "embedding": [0.025305245, -0.0015976406, 0.025726873, 0.01174648, 0.010602901, -0.023910735, -0.0045534703, -0.040848665, -0.054793205, 0.096039854, 0.032959905, -0.0031991308, 0.012328326, -0.019647626, -0.012410564, 0.013657657, -0.01731335, -0.0425822, -0.10672661, 0.03225723, 0.026628554, 0.0004964877, -0.043245785, -0.009872914, -0.028121127, 0.029732281, 0.01949685, 0.018169506, 0.042593993, 0.04149114, 0.045954764, -0.022369271, -0.0031562932, -0.040683825, 0.01721214, 0.031891696, 0.008214587, -0.02697258, 0.05008061, -0.035651598, 0.04598004, 0.02049949, 0.02832414, -0.014536097, -0.03938993, 0.02312476, -0.039486893, 0.002323723, -0.033270586, -0.0660351, 0.034011975, -0.01959921, 0.036042605, -0.00659648, 0.005033437, -0.02828433, 0.0069537056, 0.014878023, -0.02704422, -0.022874078, 0.02664916, -0.008371789, 0.032626502, -0.069998555, 0.013553509, 0.044480696, -0.017002402, 0.050530314, -0.02673437, -0.05193583, -0.027038472, -0.030723445, -0.03680095, 0.011564099, -0.06170356, 0.049449172, 0.011996808, -0.024548158, -0.060783297, -0.02324639, 0.0018943687, -0.013487241, -0.026522545, 0.0007027971, 0.022974003, -0.0295124, 0.00090072013, -0.035562523, -0.013736929, 0.010252931, 0.010705942, 0.038219195, -0.01466813, 0.0061820936, 0.042047687, 0.045970745, 0.01396591, 0.03723291, 0.025366481, -0.000324347, -0.013718732, 0.057328302, -0.0125179505, 0.058809627, -0.035642374, 0.049139503, 0.0045005116, 0.02357568, -0.008996114, -0.054099724, 0.0130952345, -0.02210574